lar MNC struggled with the pressure to be increasingly profitable while negotiating the clash of Korean and Chinese cultures, traditions, and classes on the factory floor of a garment corporation. Chinese Labor in a Korean Factory pays particular attention to common features of post-socialist countries. By analyzing the contentious collaboration between foreign management, factory workers, government officials, and gangs, this study contributes not only to the research on the politics of resistance but also to how global and local forces interact in concrete and surprising ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBusiness anthropologyzChinazQingdaovCase studies. 0aClothing factorieszChinazQingdaovCase studies. 0aCorporations, South KoreanzChinazQingdaoxSociological aspects. 0aIndustrial relationszChinazQingdaovCase studies. 0aInternational business enterpriseszChinazQingdaoxSociological aspects. 0aLabor and globalizationzChinazQingdaovCase studies. 0aLaborxAnthropological aspectszChinazQingdao. 0aSweatshopszChinazQingdaovCase studies. 4aChina. 4aSouth Korea. 4acorporate culture. 4aethnicity. 4afactory regime. 4aglobalization. 4alabor policy. 4alocalization. 4amultinational corporations (MNCs). 4apost-socialism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804786126zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804786126423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804786126.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles